{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501081"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:23:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:23:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1718"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1718"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.32,0.03,0.38,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104619"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1718"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86966"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1792"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7610"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28473"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44346"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104619"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents with a four day history of an itchy rash on his face (Image). Many years ago he had some similar episodes that completely resolved spontaneously after 7-10 days. His medical history includes several squamous cell carcinomas removed from his face, hayfever and coeliac disease. His vaccinations are up to date. On examination the rash is tender, vesicular and limited to the region shown on the photograph.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perioral dermatitis","Herpes zoster","Squamous cell carcinoma","Herpes labialis","Dermatitis herpetiformis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis clinical picture of a pruritic, vesicular rash around the naso-labial fold and on the lips is a typical presentation of\u003Cstrong\u003E herpes simplex virus (HSV). \u003C/strong\u003EThis can present as recurrent\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Evesicular eruptions that self resolve in 7-10 days without scarring. Topical acyclovir, valaciclovir, or famciclovir is usually used for treatment. Type 1 HSV is commonly associated with oral and facial infections whereas HSV Type 2 is commonly associated with genital herpes. After the initial infection, the virus resides latently in the dorsal root ganglion, and they can recur after minor trauma, any immunocompromised states, sun exposure, emotional stress etc. HSV at the nasolabial region is called Herpes labialis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerioral dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic inflammatory skin eruption that presents as an acneiform eruption, with dry surrounding skin or scaly skin surface. It is not vesicular. It usually resolves spontaneously and is common in young children, as well as women from 20 to 45 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes zoster \u003C/strong\u003Eis a vesicular eruption in a dermatomal distribution caused by the varicella zoster virus (VZV). VZV remains in the dorsal root ganglion after a primary infection of chickenpox and is reactivated as shingles, which is precipitated by 1-3 days of pain, and may cause general symptoms such as fever, lymphadenopathy and fever. Treatment with antivirals and neurological analgesic aim to prevent post-hepatic neuralgia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatitis herpetiformis \u003C/strong\u003Eusually presents symmetrically on the scalp, shoulders, buttocks, elbows and knees which does not fit the description here. It is a pruritic and commonly associated with gluten intolerance \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinomas \u003C/strong\u003Edo not present as a rash.  \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Both HSV1 and HSV2 are most infective with vesicular eruptions.","Asymptomatic serological screening for HSV types 1 or 2 are not required unless the results provide meaningful clinical information e.g. an asymptomatic pregnant partner of a newly diagnosed person."],"references":["Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (no date) DermNet. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/cutaneous-squamous-cell-carcinoma (Accessed: November 17, 2022).","Dermatitis herpetiformis (no date) DermNet. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/dermatitis-herpetiformis (Accessed: November 17, 2022).","Genital herpes simplex virus (HSV) (2022) STI Guidelines Australia. Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/genital-herpes-simplex-virus-hsv/ (Accessed: November 17, 2022).","Herpes simplex type 1 - statpearls - NCBI bookshelf (no date). Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482197/ (Accessed: November 17, 2022).","Periorificial dermatitis (no date) DermNet. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/periorificial-dermatitis (Accessed: November 17, 2022)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86966"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1718"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18352"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"ty